 Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lascelles","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from one of the large number of places in northern France called Celle, Celles, Lacelle, Leschelle, or Lachelle, all from French <i>celle</i> ‘hermitage’, and at different times occurring both with and without the plural <i>-s</i>.","Variant of   Lacelle   1, a surname of French origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Laswell","meanings":["English: possibly an altered form of   Lascelles  . This surname is also found as   Lacefield  ."]},{"name":"Lasell","meanings":["English: variant of   Lascelles  ."]},{"name":"Lacelle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alain, Andre, Aurele, Benoit, Cecile, Marcel, Marie Paule.","Altered form of French <b>Laselle</b>: habitational name from La Selle, the name of several places in various parts of France. The surname <i>Laselle</i> is very rare in France, found in Marne. Compare   Lascelles  .","In some cases possibly also French: habitational name from Lacelle in Corrèze or numerous minor places called La Celle, all named for a monastic cell or hermitage in their vicinity, from French <i>celle</i> ‘hermitage’."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger de Lascelles was born in 1110, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Picot de Lascelles, was 25 and his mother, Isabel FitzAlan, was 20. He had at least 2 sons with Theophania FitzRoald. He died in 1166, in Knowle, Warwickshire, England, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1110–1166":"1110–1166","1130–1176":"1130–1176","1129–1178":"1129–1178","1148–1176":"1148–1176","1158–1211":"1158–1211","1085–1129":"1085–1129","1090–1177":"1090–1177","1090":"1090","1110":"1110","1176":"1176","1130":"1130","1085":"1085","1129":"1129","1148":"1148","1158":"1158","1211":"1211","1178":"1178","1166":"1166","1177":"1177","about 1158":"umbes 1158","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Kirby Knowle, Yorkshire, England":"Kirby Knowle, Yorkshire, England","Escrick, Yorkshire, England":"Escrick, Yorkshire, England","Knowle, Warwickshire, England":"Knowle, Warwickshire, England"},"fi":{"1110–1166":"1110–1166","1130–1176":"1130–1176","1129–1178":"1129–1178","1148–1176":"1148–1176","1158–1211":"1158–1211","1085–1129":"1085–1129","1090–1177":"1090–1177","1090":"1090","1110":"1110","1176":"1176","1130":"1130","1085":"1085","1129":"1129","1148":"1148","1158":"1158","1211":"1211","1178":"1178","1166":"1166","1177":"1177","about 1158":"noin 1158","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Kirby Knowle, Yorkshire, England":"Kirby K